\section{Short Channel Effects}

RF performance of a MESFET depends on its $L_g$ and saturation velocity, $\upsilon_s$ of its carriers. With reduction in $L_g$, an obvious benefit is an increase in $f_T$. However, when $L_g$ is less than 1$\mu$m, the device suffers from short channel effects and performance of the device is degraded \cite{Yim2011}, which included reduction in $g_m$ and an increase in $g_d$ of the device as shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:2.1} \cite{Honda2003}. The figure shows that $g_m$ increases from 25.9 to 30 mS mm$^{-1}$ as  $L_g$ decreases form 1.5 to 0.8$\mu $m and decreases from 30 to 24.6 mS mm$^{-1}$  as $L_g$ decreases from 0.8 to 0.3$ \mu $m. The figure also indicates that $g_d$ increases from 2.2 to 6.45 mS mm$^{-1}$ as $L_g$ decreases from 1.5 to 0.3$ \mu $m.

\begin{figure}
\centering
%\includegraphics [scale=0.5]{3D}
\includegraphics [width=4.5in, height=4in]{ThesisFigs/Fig2_1.pdf}
\caption{$g_m$ and $g_d$ as function of $L_g$.}
\label{Fig:2.1}
\end{figure}

In short channel devices, the horizontal electric field becomes stronger and even at smaller drain biasing, the mobility of carriers starts to reduce. Young et al. \cite{Cha2005}, in their study of transport characteristics of SiC MESFETs, reported that $\upsilon_s$ and the low field mobility, $\mu_0$ of the carriers are 1.7$\times$10$^7$ cm/s and 300 cm$^2$/Vs, respectively, which are smaller than previously reported values.

Another important short channel effect is drain induced barrier lowering (DIBL). Primarily, Schottky barrier depletion layer is controlled by the gate biasing. However, with increased drain biasing, there is an enhancement in charge layer accumulation near the drain-side of the gate. These charges create their image charges in the gate electrode, as a result, there is a reduction in the magnitude of gate potential, which reduces Schottky barrier called as DIBL. In short channel devices, this effect becomes more prominent and leads to an increase in $g_d$.

Furthermore, in short channel devices, carriers become hot due to high field available in the channel and get diverted towards the substrate, resulting in large substrate current. Honda et al. \cite{Honda2003} and Manabu et al. \cite{Arai2003} in their respective investigations of short channel effects, observed that when $L_g$ is less than 1$\mu$m, gate loses its control over the channel current due to DIBL. As a result, $f_T$ and $f_{max}$ started to saturate and at $L_g$ $\sim$ 0.3$\mu$m, they were even less than the maximum values as shown in Fig. \ref{Fig:2.2}. They also observed that $g_d$ increases and $V_T$ shifts towards more negative values to pinch off the channel. Moreover, $V_T$ also became strong function of $V_{ds}$ and increases with its increasing values. Furthermore, power density (PD) also starts to reduce by decreasing the gate width as evident from Fig. \ref{Fig:2.3}.

